# Setup

The demo convinced you and you'd like to use CSA Admin for your CSA? Here's how the setup works. It's simple and only requires a few steps on your end. I take care of the rest!

## 1. Subdomains {#subdomains}

CSA Admin uses two subdomains attached to your own domain name, one for the admin interface, one for your members:

- **admin**`.your-domain.com` gives you access to the admin interface (like the one in the demo)
- **members**`.your-domain.com` is where your members log in, register, and manage their account

Setting up these subdomains requires access to the DNS server of your domain name (usually at the same place as your website host). The simplest way is to temporarily invite me to your account so I can make the necessary changes. If you prefer, I can also provide the DNS entries so you can add them yourself.

On top of the subdomains, there are also two extra DNS entries to add for configuring email delivery from your domain. Don't worry, these additions don't affect your existing website or emails in any way, everything continues to work normally alongside.

## 2. I take care of the rest {#setup}

Once the DNS entries are in place, I handle everything on my side:

- Creating your organization and admin account
- Setting up email delivery from your domain
- SSL certificates, hosting, backups, ...

## Pricing {#pricing}

Details about the program's cost are available on [csa-admin.org](https://csa-admin.org/#pricing). It is calculated based on the amount invoiced through CSA Admin. The first year, I base it on the total expected invoicing amount for the current fiscal year, so you can try the program at no cost until your first delivery. After that, the total amount invoiced from 01.01 to 12.31 of the previous year is used, at the beginning of January.

